---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';

const title = 'Free QR Codes That Never Expire — Static vs Dynamic | QRMint';
const description = 'Most free QR codes expire. Ours do not. Here is why: static QR codes encode all data in the image itself. No server, no expiration, forever.';

const canonical = new URL('/no-expiration/', Astro.site).href;

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'WebApplication',
  name: 'QR Codes That Never Expire — QRMint',
  url: canonical,
  applicationCategory: 'MultimediaApplication',
  operatingSystem: 'Any (Web Browser)',
  description,
  offers: { '@type': 'Offer', price: '0', priceCurrency: 'USD' },
};

const comparisons = [
  { type: 'Static QR (ours)', how: 'Data encoded in the image', expires: 'Never', editable: 'No (re-generate)', tracking: 'No', cost: 'Free forever' },
  { type: 'Dynamic QR', how: 'Data stored on a server', expires: 'Yes (usually 6-12mo)', editable: 'Yes', tracking: 'Yes', cost: 'Free tier, then $7-9/mo' },
];
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical} jsonLd={jsonLd}>
  <Header />
  <main class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-4 py-10">
    <section class="text-center">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-slate-900 sm:text-4xl">Your QR Code Stops Working? Ours Do Not.</h1>
      <p class="mx-auto mt-4 max-w-2xl text-lg text-slate-600">
        If you have ever printed a QR code from a free tool only to find it dead six months later, 
        you have been bitten by the dynamic QR trap. Here is how to spot it — and how ours works differently.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-10 rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Static vs Dynamic QR Codes</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full text-left text-sm">
          <thead class="bg-slate-50">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-slate-700" scope="col"></th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-green-700" scope="col">Static QR (ours)</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-slate-700" scope="col">Dynamic QR (most tools)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-slate-100">
            {comparisons.map((row) => (
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-slate-800">{row.type}</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-700">{row.how}</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-slate-600">{row.how}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-4 text-xs text-slate-400">
        With a static QR, the data is in the image. Print it on a billboard in 2026 and someone scanning it in 2050 will still see the same content.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-xs text-slate-400">* Pricing and feature data based on publicly available information as of July 2026. May have changed since.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-12 space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">When Static QR Makes Sense — and When It Does Not</h2>
      <p class="text-slate-600">Static QR codes encode everything in the image itself. When you scan them, your phone reads the URL directly from the black-and-white pattern. No redirect, no server log, no expiration.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-600">Dynamic QR codes store a short URL on a server. The scanner hits that short URL and gets redirected to the real destination. This lets the provider track scans and, crucially, change where the code points later — at the cost of making the code dependent on a server that can go down or stop being paid for.</p>
      <p class="text-sm font-medium text-slate-700">Go to the <a href="/" class="text-brand-600 underline">homepage tool</a> — every QR it generates is static and permanent.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-12 space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">FAQ</h2>
      <details class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 p-4">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer font-medium text-slate-800">How can I tell if a QR code is static or dynamic?</summary>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-600">Hard to tell by looking. But if a free tool asks you to create an account, it is almost certainly dynamic. If it shows you scan analytics, it is dynamic. If it says your code will "expire" unless you upgrade, it is dynamic.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 p-4">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer font-medium text-slate-800">Can I update a static QR code after printing it?</summary>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-600">No — that is the trade-off. Static codes cannot be edited. If your URL changes, you need a new code. For printed materials that do not change often (business cards, menus, product labels), this is rarely an issue. If you need editing, you need a dynamic code (and a paid tool).</p>
      </details>
      <details class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 p-4">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer font-medium text-slate-800">Do you offer dynamic codes as a premium feature?</summary>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-600">Not yet. For now we focus on making static QR generation as fast and private as possible. Premium dynamic codes (editable, trackable) are on the roadmap.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Layout>
